welcome to History 210, The

00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:06.133
Early Middle Ages.

00:00:06.133 --> 00:00:08.000
I'm Paul Freedman.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.033
And behind this innocuous
title "The

00:00:11.033 --> 00:00:11.967
Early Middle Ages"--

00:00:11.967 --> 00:00:14.167
I think we're going to have
to jazz it up a little.

00:00:14.167 --> 00:00:17.233
I think we're going to put an
exclamation mark on it, at

00:00:17.233 --> 00:00:21.167
least. But behind this innocuous
title, you will see,

00:00:21.167 --> 00:00:27.067
I hope, if you stay for this
course, a strange course.

00:00:27.067 --> 00:00:33.533
Strange, not because it covers
the particular period 250 to

00:00:33.533 --> 00:00:39.100
1000, but because it starts
out very recognizable, and

00:00:39.100 --> 00:00:42.667
gets stranger and stranger, and
seems to dissolve into a

00:00:42.667 --> 00:00:47.033
kind of a hard to grasp world.

00:00:47.033 --> 00:00:48.300
Hard to grasp, but fun.

00:00:48.300 --> 00:00:50.833
I will talk about both the
strangeness and the fun

00:00:50.833 --> 00:00:54.300
aspects in more detail.

00:00:54.300 --> 00:00:58.167
There are several great themes
in this span of centuries: the

00:00:58.167 --> 00:01:04.100
fall of the Roman Empire; its
survival in the East, as the

00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:08.600
Byzantine Empire; the so-called
barbarian invasions

00:01:08.600 --> 00:01:13.433
and kingdoms, set up on the
ruins of the Roman Empire; the

00:01:13.433 --> 00:01:16.600
triumph of Christianity, which
went from being an outlawed

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:20.033
minority religion to the
established faith of the Roman

00:01:20.033 --> 00:01:23.267
Empire; and then survived
the extinction

00:01:23.267 --> 00:01:25.700
of the Roman Empire.

