00:09:49.967 --> 00:09:53.967
We are beginning by looking
at the crisis

00:09:53.967 --> 00:09:55.500
of the Roman Empire.

00:09:55.500 --> 00:09:59.533
And then we will be looking
at its peculiar legacy.

00:09:59.533 --> 00:10:03.267
In the year 1000, where we stop,
we will still be dealing

00:10:03.267 --> 00:10:08.367
with The Inheritance of the
Roman Empire, the title of

00:10:08.367 --> 00:10:10.433
Chris Wickham's book, one of the
books that we're going to

00:10:10.433 --> 00:10:13.467
be using a lot.

00:10:13.467 --> 00:10:17.233
The legacy is peculiar because,
while the memory of

00:10:17.233 --> 00:10:22.233
the Roman Empire remains intact
throughout the period,

00:10:22.233 --> 00:10:23.000
and beyond--

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.100
I mean, to this day, the
head of the Catholic

00:10:25.100 --> 00:10:28.400
Church is in Rome.

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:35.133
Until 1960, the transactions of
the papacy were in Latin:

00:10:35.133 --> 00:10:38.467
the services of the Church were
in Latin, the Catholic

00:10:38.467 --> 00:10:39.733
Church were in Latin.

00:10:39.733 --> 00:10:44.133
And Latin remains the official
language of the Catholic

00:10:44.133 --> 00:10:46.633
church in its administrative
head.

00:10:46.633 --> 00:10:53.033
So the most faithful preserver
of Rome and its legacy,

00:10:53.033 --> 00:10:57.133
historically, is the
Catholic Church.

00:10:57.133 --> 00:11:00.967
And this is a paradox because
the Church begins its career,

00:11:00.967 --> 00:11:05.133
and, indeed, its first
250 years, as illegal

00:11:05.133 --> 00:11:06.300
in the Roman empire.

00:11:06.300 --> 00:11:08.633
And, indeed, there are periodic
persecutions where

00:11:08.633 --> 00:11:13.533
people were punished, including
killed, because they

00:11:13.533 --> 00:11:14.800
were Christian.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:21.367
The most faithful preserver of
Rome, however, after the fifth

00:11:21.367 --> 00:11:24.700
century collapse of the Empire
in the West, is the so-called

00:11:24.700 --> 00:11:26.700
Byzantine Empire--

00:11:26.700 --> 00:11:31.067
the Byzantine Empire with
its headquarters in

00:11:31.067 --> 00:11:32.300
Constantinople.

00:11:34.267 --> 00:11:37.533
Despite the fact that it would
abandon Latin for Greek in the

00:11:37.533 --> 00:11:40.567
sixth century and turn into
a very different kind of

00:11:40.567 --> 00:11:45.867
political and cultural entity,
the Byzantine Empire went down

00:11:45.867 --> 00:11:53.400
in flames to the Turks in 1453
still as the Roman Empire.

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:56.867
That was its official
name to the end.

00:12:00.433 --> 00:12:05.433
Another heir to the Roman
Empire, in a sense, is Islam,

00:12:05.433 --> 00:12:08.500
which begins in the seventh
century, in the

00:12:08.500 --> 00:12:10.267
middle of our period.

00:12:10.267 --> 00:12:12.900
I don't have to emphasize
to you the historical

00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:16.100
importance of Islam.

00:12:16.100 --> 00:12:20.367
But our task is to understand
its origin and its astonishing

00:12:20.367 --> 00:12:27.333
expansion in terms of this
era, 250 to 1000.

00:12:27.333 --> 00:12:30.733
To understand it in terms of
its times, and thus how it

00:12:30.733 --> 00:12:37.000
arises and interacts with the
Roman and Byzantine as well

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:41.267
as, offstage, the Persian,
Empires that it either

00:12:41.267 --> 00:12:45.667
destroys or weakens in the
seventh and eighth centuries.

00:12:45.667 --> 00:12:49.433
Mohammed was from outside the
former empire, from Arabia,

00:12:49.433 --> 00:12:51.567
and may be said to represent
a very different

00:12:51.567 --> 00:12:53.900
kind of set of ideas.

00:12:58.233 --> 00:13:02.367
But the power of Islam would,
for centuries, be concentrated

00:13:02.367 --> 00:13:06.667
in areas of the former Roman
Empire: the Mediterranean, the

00:13:06.667 --> 00:13:09.133
Balkans, Egypt, Syria,
North Africa.

00:13:09.133 --> 00:13:13.233
Of course, in the latter, it
still is the overwhelming

00:13:13.233 --> 00:13:14.467
majority religion.

00:13:17.600 --> 00:13:22.767
And Islam then brings up a sort
of question that I'm not

00:13:22.767 --> 00:13:26.167
going to deal with directly very
much, but that will be at

00:13:26.167 --> 00:13:29.367
the back of our minds, and
that is relevance.

00:13:29.367 --> 00:13:32.167
This is a pre-industrial course;
it's in the very

00:13:32.167 --> 00:13:35.533
pre-industrial category in
terms of requirements.

00:13:35.533 --> 00:13:37.967
It's far away; it's distant.

00:13:37.967 --> 00:13:40.933
That is part of its appeal,
I think, is as I said, its

00:13:40.933 --> 00:13:42.867
strangeness.

00:13:42.867 --> 00:13:46.000
But the lessons from the
material covered in this

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.100
course are perhaps these--

00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:49.733
worth thinking about.

00:13:52.267 --> 00:13:56.267
How, perhaps the most
successful, multi-cultural

00:13:56.267 --> 00:14:02.800
empire of Western history, how
it did that, how it endured

00:14:02.800 --> 00:14:03.733
for so long.

00:14:03.733 --> 00:14:07.200
The success of the
Roman Empire and

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:10.067
why it finally failed.

00:14:10.067 --> 00:14:15.367
And in that failure, how
does a rich, literate,

00:14:15.367 --> 00:14:21.667
well-developed society come
to be destroyed by a more

00:14:21.667 --> 00:14:22.733
primitive one?

00:14:22.733 --> 00:14:26.500
Primitive, at least, in the
sense of material culture,

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:30.133
economic complexity,
urbanization, and literacy.

00:14:33.333 --> 00:14:38.933
Another important lesson is the
power of religious ideas,

00:14:38.933 --> 00:14:44.967
not only intrinsically as part
of people's lives and outlook,

00:14:44.967 --> 00:14:51.000
but socially and historically:
how religion affects the

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.533
political course of history.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.333
Having said this, I think I did
